# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-crombie-humphreys
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-davison-bailey] Bailey was born in what is now Salem Lakes, Wisconsin, son of Eugene M.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-davison-bailey] He obtained his BSc in Mechanical Engineering in 1903 from the Lewis Institute in Chicago, now Illinois Institute of Technology.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-davison-bailey] Before his graduation Bailey had started his career as draftsman at the U.S Wind Engine and Pump Company in Batavia, Illinois, and had been trouble man at the Evanston Heating Co. in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-davison-bailey] After his graduation Bailey started his lifelong career at the Chicago Edison Co., soon to be Commonwealth Edison.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-davison-bailey] From 1903 to 1905 he started as draftsman, from 1906 to 1916 he was assistant chief engineer at Fisk Street Station, and another chief engineer.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-davison-bailey] From 1921 to 1932 he was superintendent of generating stations of the company, and in 1933 appointed assistant chief operating engineer.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-davison-bailey] From 1936 to 1942 he was chief operating engineer and manager of the Super Power department.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-davison-bailey] The last years ten years at the company he was vice-president in charge of operations and engineering.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-davison-bailey] He retired on February 1, 1952 after 48 years of service.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-davison-bailey] In 1942 Bailey had been awarded the Honorary Doctor of Science by the Northwestern University.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-dow] Dow was born in Glasgow, Scotland as son of William Dow, a blacksmith, and Jean (Keppy) Dow in 1862.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-dow] He emigrated to the US in 1882 at the age of twenty.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-dow] In 1893 Dow was appointed the first plant manager of the first municipally owned power plant in Detroit, and electrical engineer for the city of Detroit.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-dow] The power plant had been built as a result of Hazen Pingree's efforts to break the power of corporations over Detroit City politics.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-dow] It was during this time that Henry Ford worked under Dow at one of the Detroit Edison substations.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-dow] Dow took Ford with him to the 1896 annual convention of the Association of Edison Illuminating Companies being held that year in New York City.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-dow] It was at this convention that Dow introduced Ford to Thomas Edison, the meeting with, and encouragement from, the great scientist becoming a great inspiration to Ford in completing his first car.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-dow] Dow was appointed water commissioner for the city of Detroit in 1916-1921 and again in 1925-1932.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-dow] In 1932, he was made the president of Detroit Edison and served until 1940.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-dow] He was elected president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers for the 1928-1929 year.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-dow] He was a member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, American Society of Civil Engineers, American Institute of Electrical Engineers, Institute of Electrical Engineers (Great Britain), Institute of Mechanical Engineers (Great Britain).
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alex-dow] Dow also served as the President of The Engineering Society of Detroit from 1900-1901.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was born in Edinburgh, Scotland on 30 March 1851 to Edward Rupert Humphreys, an English classical scholar and profound educator, and Margaret McNutt of Prince Edward Island.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He attended his father's school in Boston after coming to the United States in 1859.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] At the age of fourteen he received an appointment and passed preliminary entrance exams for the United States Naval Academy before the academy discovered he was too young to complete entrance.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He instead began working for insurance companies and was made Secretary-Treasurer of the New York Guaranty and Indemnity Company by 1872, he became superintendent shortly thereafter.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He later became superintendent of the Bayonne and Greenville Gas Light Company and attended Stevens Institute of Technology earning his degree in mechanical engineering; he graduated in 1881.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1892 he founded Humphreys & Glasgow, Engineering, London and New York with Arthur G.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys continued his career with the Pintsch Lighting Company of New York, the United Gas Improvement Company, and the Weisbach Incandescent Gas Company.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In April 1872 he married Miss Eva Guillandeu of Bergen Point, NJ.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] They had three children in total: Harold, Crombie and Dorothy Caroline Humphreys-Turnbull.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of his son Harold, who was also the first son of a Stevens alumnus to graduate from the college, he endowed the Harold Humphreys Scholarship in 1902.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of Crombie, who drowned with Harold in the Nile in 1901, the Crombie Humphreys Scholarship in 1904.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1927, Alexander Crombie Humphreys lost a battle with cancer.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] His death came two years after serving as President of his Alma mater for a quarter of a century, and chairman of the board of trustees for two years.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] The only immediate family member to outlive him was his daughter.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Following the death of Henry Morton in 1902, the board of trustees of Stevens Institute of Technology unanimously called upon Humphreys to serve his Alma mater as president.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Prior to his presidency, Humphreys was elected a trustee of the institute on 23 December 1891 and served as chair of the Stevens Alumni Association from 1883 to 1886.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys developed the institute as one of the first technical schools in the United States.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During a dinner following his inauguration, Colonel Edwin A.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, Jr., son of the school's founder Edwin A.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, presented the institute with a plot of land on which to construct a dormitory.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon assuming the office of President, Humphreys requested of Andrew Carnegie the financial support to construct a new building.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He followed this with an address to the Board of Trustees urging construction of the Morton Laboratory of Chemistry, a dormitory, a gymnasium and library – a "crying need of the Institute".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] As a homage to his predecessor, Humphreys campaigned for the creation of the Morton Memorial Chemistry Laboratory and commissioned a book on Stevens' founding and its early years to be named in his honor.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] These initiatives were but foreshadowing of the growth Humphreys would bring to Stevens.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1924 the campus grew from just over a city block to 23-acres, enrollment quadrupled and endowment grew to $2,864,000 (from $384,800 when Humprheys took office).
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] That year also marked the successful end of the "Million Dollar Campaign", which had attracted donations from alumni as well as George Eastman and Edward Harkness.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1909, Stevens seized the opportunity to acquire Castle Point from Richard Stevens inclusive of the prominent Stevens Family Castle constructed in 1853; the purchase was primarily funded by the Carnegie Foundation and John D.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] This came within months of acquiring the land adjacent to present-day 8th street upon which fraternity houses were constructed that stand to this day.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1960 the Institute expanded again and constructed two residence halls, one of which bared his name.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the growth of the institute, Alexander C.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys felt it important to impart engineering students with a sense of business – a tool that would be essential in their success in all lines of manufacturing.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He began teaching the first courses on this topic in 1903 and is regarded as the father of Engineering Economics.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] To honor his contributions, Stevens Institute of Technology endows an Alexander Crombie Humphreys Chair in Economics of Engineering.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the dinner of his inauguration, Humphreys announced that one of his ambitions was to start an Honor System at Stevens to cover academic work.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was very adamant that the creation of such a system come from the students and on the first page of the first issue of the school newspaper "The Stute" appeared an article written by a junior urging the implementation of such.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1908 the students created a self run Honor Board who was charged with investigating cases, bringing up charges, judging cases by a vote and recommend punishments to the faculty.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon Humphreys' recommendation, faculty were also required to abide by such a pledge in administering exams within Honor Board guidelines on the grounds that it is a "...proviso apply[ing] to the examiner as well as to the student".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-graham-christie] Christie was born in Manchester, Ontario, Canada to Peter Christie and Mary Honor (Graham) Christie.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-graham-christie] He obtained his MSc in mechanical engineering at the School of Practical Science at the University of Toronto in 1901.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-graham-christie] After his graduation Christie started as an apprentice in the engineering shop of the Westinghouse Machine Company.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-graham-christie] After the introduction of its first steam turbine, Christie specialized in that field.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-graham-christie] By 1909 he was research Assistant in Steam and Gas Engineering at the University of Wisconsin, and associate professor of Steam and Gas Engineering by 1914.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-graham-christie] In 1914 he moved to the Johns Hopkins University, where he became associate professor, and later Professor of Engineering until his retirement in 1948, and director of the McCoy College until 1953.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-graham-christie] In 1939-40 Christie served as president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-graham-christie] He was awarded the honorary doctor in engineering by the Stevens Institute of Technology in 1939, and by the Lehigh University in 1940.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-graham-christie] The American Society for Engineering Education awarded Christie the Lamme Gold Medal in 1948, and the first George Westinghouse Gold Medal for engineering by the ASME in 1953.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alexander-graham-christie] At the Johns Hopkins Whiting school of Engineer an annual lecture is held on his behalf, the Alexander Graham Christie Lecture.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] In its earliest usage, *alma mater* was an honorific title for various mother goddesses, especially Ceres or Cybele.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] Later, in Catholicism, it became a title for Mary, mother of Jesus.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] By the early 17th century, the nursing mother became an allegory for universities.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] Used by many schools in Europe and North America, it has special association with the University of Bologna, whose motto *Alma Mater Studiorum* ("nurturing mother of studies") emphasizes its role in originating the modern university.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] Several university campuses in North America display artistic representations of *Alma Mater*, depicted as a robed woman wearing a laurel wreath crown.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] The earliest and of these is the bronze *Alma Mater* statue at Columbia University, designed in 1901 by Daniel Chester French.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] In the US the term *alma mater* is often used to describe a school song.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] Although *alma* (nourishing) was a common epithet for Ceres, Cybele, Venus, and other mother goddesses, it was not frequently used in conjunction with *mater* in classical Latin.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] After the fall of Rome, the term was used in Christian liturgy to describe Jesus' mother, Mary.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] "Alma Redemptoris Mater" is a well-known eleventh century antiphon devoted to Mary.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] The earliest documented use of the term to refer to a university is in 1600, when the University of Cambridge printer, John Legate, began using an emblem for the university press.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] The first-known appearance of the device is in William Perkins', *A Golden Chain*, a book first printed by Legate in 1600.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] On the title-page, the Latin phrase *Alma Mater Cantabrigia* ("nourishing mother Cambridge") is inscribed on a pedestal bearing a lactating woman wearing a mural crown.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] In reference works of English etymology, often the first university-related usage is cited as 1710, when an academic mother figure is mentioned in a remembrance of Henry More by Richard Ward.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] Many historic European universities have adopted *Alma Mater* as part of the Latin translation of their official name.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] The Latin name of the University of Bologna, *Alma Mater Studiorum* (nourishing mother of studies), refers to its status as the oldest continuously operating university in the world.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] At other European universities, such as the Alma Mater Lipsiensis in Leipzig, Germany, or Alma Mater Jagiellonica, Poland, the title emphasizes historic ties to a founding city or dynasty.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] The Alma Mater Europaea in Salzburg, Austria, an international university founded by the European Academy of Sciences and Arts in 2010, uses the term as its official name.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] In the United States, the College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia, has been called the "Alma Mater of the Nation" because of its ties to the founding of the country.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] At Queen's University in Kingston, Ontario, and the University of British Columbia in Vancouver, British Columbia, the main student government is known as the Alma Mater Society.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] Sculptures of *Alma Mater* are found on several North American university campuses.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] In 1901, to commemorate the opening of the Low Library, Columbia University commissioned Daniel Chester French to design a bronze statue for the library's steps.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] French chose the *Alma Mater* to allegorically embody the university without depicting its founder, King George II.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] A similar sculpture, cast in 1919 by Mario Korbel, sits on the main entrance steps at the University of Havana.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] Other tributes to *Alma Mater* include Lorado Taft's *1929 sculpture* at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign and Cyrus Dallin's 1925 sculpture at the Mary Institute in 1925, commissioned by Washington University supporters.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/alma-mater] An altarpiece mural in Yale University's Sterling Memorial Library, painted in 1932 by Eugene Savage, depicts the *Alma Mater* as a bearer of light and truth, standing in the midst of figures representing the arts and sciences.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He became a leading philanthropist in the United States, Great Britain, and the British Empire.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] During the last 18 years of his life, he gave away around $350 million (equivalent to $6.9 billion in 2025 dollars), almost 90 percent of his fortune, to charities, foundations and universities.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] His 1889 article proclaiming "The Gospel of Wealth" called on the rich to use their wealth to improve society, expressed support for progressive taxation and an estate tax, and stimulated a wave of philanthropy.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie was born in Dunfermline, Scotland.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He immigrated to what is now Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, with his parents in 1848 at the age of 12.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie started work in a cotton mill and later as a telegrapher.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] By the 1860s, he had investments in railroads, railroad sleeping cars, bridges, and oil derricks.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He accumulated further wealth as a bond salesman, raising money for American enterprise in Europe.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He built Pittsburgh's Carnegie Steel Company, which he sold to J.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] After selling Carnegie Steel, he surpassed John D.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Rockefeller as the richest American of the time.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie devoted the remainder of his life to large-scale philanthropy, with special emphasis on building local libraries, working for world peace, education, and scientific research.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Andrew Carnegie was born to William Carnegie and Margaret (Morrison) Carnegie in Dunfermline, Scotland, in a typical weaver's cottage with only one main room.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] It consisted of half the ground floor, which was shared with the neighboring weaver's family.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The main room served as a living room, dining room and bedroom.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He was named after his paternal grandfather.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] William Carnegie had a successful weaving business and owned multiple looms.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1836, the family moved to a larger house in Edgar Street (opposite Reid's Park), following the demand for more heavy damask, from which his father benefited.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie was educated at the Free School in Dunfermline, a gift to the town from philanthropist Adam Rolland of Gask.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie's maternal uncle, Scottish political leader George Lauder Sr., deeply influenced him as a boy by introducing him to Robert Burns' writings and historical Scottish heroes such as Robert the Bruce, William Wallace, and Rob Roy.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Lauder's son, also named George Lauder, grew up with Carnegie and later became his business partner in the United States.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] When Carnegie was 12, his father had fallen on tough times as a handloom weaver.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Making matters worse, the country was in starvation.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] His mother helped support the family by assisting her brother and by selling potted meats at her "sweetie shop", becoming the primary breadwinner.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Struggling to make ends meet, the Carnegies decided to borrow money from George Lauder, Sr. and move to the United States in 1848 for the prospect of a better life.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] They headed to Allegheny, Pennsylvania, where they heard there was a demand for workers.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie's emigration to America was his second journey outside Dunfermline.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The first was a family outing to Edinburgh to see Queen Victoria.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In September 1848, Carnegie and his family arrived in Allegheny.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie's father struggled to sell his product on his own.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Eventually, the father and son both received job offers at Anchor Cotton Mills, a Scottish-owned facility.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie's first job in 1848 was as a bobbin boy, changing spools of thread in a cotton mill 12 hours a day, 6 days a week in a Pittsburgh cotton factory.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] His starting wage was $1.20 per week (equivalent to $45 in 2025).
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] His father soon quit his position at the cotton mill, returning to his loom, and was again removed as a substantial breadwinner.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] But Carnegie attracted the attention of John Hay, a Scottish manufacturer of bobbins, who offered him a job for $2.00 per week (equivalent to $74 in 2025).
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1849, Carnegie became a telegraph messenger boy in the Pittsburgh Office of the Ohio Telegraph Company, following the recommendation of his uncle.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He was a hard worker and would memorize all of the locations of Pittsburgh's businesses and the faces of important men.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He also paid close attention to his work and quickly learned to distinguish the different sounds the incoming telegraph signals produced.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He developed the ability to translate signals by ear, without using the paper slip.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Within a year he was promoted to an operator.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie's education and passion for reading were given a boost by Colonel James Anderson, who opened his personal library of 400 volumes to working boys each Saturday night.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie was a consistent borrower and a "self-made man" in both his economic development and his intellectual and cultural development.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He was so grateful to Colonel Anderson for the use of his library that he "resolved, if ever wealth came to me, [to see to it] that other poor boys might receive opportunities similar to those for which we were indebted to the nobleman".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Starting in 1853, when Carnegie was around 18 years old, Thomas A.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Scott of the Pennsylvania Railroad employed him as a secretary/telegraph operator at a salary of $4.00 per week ($155 by 2025).
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie accepted the job with the railroad as he saw more prospects for career growth and experience there than with the telegraph company.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] When Carnegie was 24 years old, Scott asked him if he could handle being superintendent of the Western Division of the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] On December 1, 1859, Carnegie officially became superintendent of the Western Division.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He hired his sixteen-year-old brother Tom to be his personal secretary and telegraph operator.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie also hired his cousin, Maria Hogan, who became the first female telegraph operator in the country.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] As superintendent, Carnegie made a salary of $1500 a year ($54,000 by 2025 inflation).
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] His employment by the Pennsylvania Railroad would be vital to his later success.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The railroads were the first big businesses in America, and the Pennsylvania was one of the largest.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie learned much about management and cost control during these years, and from Scott in particular.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Scott also helped him with his first investments.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Many of these were part of the corruption indulged in by Scott and the president of the Pennsylvania Railroad, John Edgar Thomson, which consisted of inside trading in companies with which the railroad did business, or payoffs made by contracting parties "as part of a *quid pro quo*".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1855, Scott made it possible for Carnegie to invest $500 in the Adams Express Company, which contracted with the Pennsylvania to carry its messengers.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The money was secured by his mother's placing of a $600 mortgage on the family's $700 home, but the opportunity was available only because of Carnegie's close relationship with Scott.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] A few years later, he received a few shares in Theodore Tuttle Woodruff's sleeping car company as a reward for holding shares that Woodruff had given to Scott and Thomson, as a payoff.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Reinvesting his returns in such inside investments in railroad-related industries (iron, bridges, and rails), Carnegie slowly accumulated capital, the basis for his later success.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Throughout his later career, he made use of his close connections to Thomson and Scott, as he established businesses that supplied rails and bridges to the railroad, offering the two men stakes in his enterprises.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Before the American Civil War, Carnegie arranged a merger between Woodruff's company and that of George Pullman, the inventor of the sleeping car for first-class travel, which facilitated business travel at distances over 500 miles (800 km).
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The investment proved a success and a source of profit for Woodruff and Carnegie.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The young Carnegie continued to work for Pennsylvania's Tom Scott and introduced several improvements in the service.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In the spring of 1861, Carnegie joined the U.S.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Military Telegraph Corps and was appointed by Scott, who was now Assistant Secretary of War in charge of military transportation, as Superintendent of the Military Railways and the Union Government's telegraph lines in the East.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie helped open the rail lines into Washington D.C. that the rebels had cut; he rode the locomotive pulling the first brigade of Union troops to reach Washington D.C.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Following the defeat of Union forces at Bull Run, he personally supervised the transportation of the defeated forces.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Under his organization, the telegraph service rendered efficient service to the Union cause and significantly assisted in the eventual victory.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie later joked that he was "the first casualty of the war" when he gained a scar on his cheek from freeing a trapped telegraph wire.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The defeat of the Confederacy required vast supplies of munitions, with railroads and telegraph lines being required to deliver them efficiently.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The war demonstrated how integral the industries were to Union success.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1864, Carnegie was one of the early investors in the Columbia Oil Company in Venango County, Pennsylvania.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In one year, the firm yielded over $1 million in cash dividends, and petroleum from oil wells on the property sold profitably.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The demand for iron products, such as armor for gunboats, cannons, and shells, as well as a hundred other industrial products, made Pittsburgh a center of wartime production.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie worked with others in establishing a steel rolling mill, and steel production and control of industry became the source of his fortune.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie had some investments in the iron industry before the war.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] After the war, Carnegie left the railroads to devote his energies to the ironworks trade.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie worked to develop several ironworks, eventually forming the Keystone Bridge Works and the Union Ironworks, in Pittsburgh.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Although he had left the Pennsylvania Railroad Company, he remained connected to its management, namely Thomas A.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He used his connection to the two men to acquire contracts for his Keystone Bridge Company and the rails produced by his ironworks.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He also gave stock in his businesses to Scott and Thomson, and the Pennsylvania was his best customer.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] When he built his first steel plant, he made a point of naming it after Thomson.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] As well as having good business sense, Carnegie possessed charm and literary knowledge.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He was invited to many important social functions, which Carnegie exploited to his advantage.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie, through Keystone, supplied the steel for and owned shares in the landmark Eads Bridge project across the Mississippi River at St.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] This project was an important proof-of-concept for steel technology, which marked the opening of a new steel market.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie believed in using his fortune for others and doing more than making money.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie made his fortune in the steel industry, controlling the most extensive integrated iron and steel operations ever owned by an individual in the United States.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] One of his two great innovations was in the cheap and efficient mass production of steel by adopting and adapting the Bessemer process, which allowed the high carbon content of pig iron to be burnt away in a controlled and rapid way during steel production.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Steel prices dropped as a result, and Bessemer steel was rapidly adopted for rails; however, it was not suitable for buildings and bridges.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The second was in his vertical integration of all suppliers of raw materials.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1883, Carnegie bought the rival Homestead Steel Works, which included an extensive plant served by tributary coal and iron fields, a 425-mile-long (684 km) railway, and a line of lake steamships.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In the late 1880s, Carnegie Steel was the largest manufacturer of pig iron, steel rails, and coke in the world, with a capacity to produce approximately 2,000 tons of pig iron per day.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] By 1889, the U.S. output of steel exceeded that of the UK, and Carnegie owned a large part of it.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie's empire grew to include the J.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie combined his assets and those of his associates in 1892 with the launching of the Carnegie Steel Company.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie's success was also due to his relationship with the railroad industries, which not only relied on steel for track, but were also making money from steel transport.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The steel and railroad barons worked closely to negotiate prices instead of allowing free-market competition.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Besides Carnegie's market manipulation, United States trade tariffs were also working in favor of the steel industry.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie spent energy and resources lobbying Congress for a continuation of favorable tariffs from which he earned millions of dollars a year.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie tried to keep this information concealed, but legal documents released in 1900, during proceedings with the ex-chairman of Carnegie Steel, Henry Clay Frick, revealed how favorable the tariffs had been.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1901, Carnegie was 65 years of age and considering retirement.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He reformed his enterprises into conventional joint stock corporations as preparation for this.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] John Pierpont Morgan was a banker and America's most important financial deal maker.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He had observed how efficiently Carnegie produced profits.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He envisioned an integrated steel industry that would cut costs, lower prices to consumers, produce in greater quantities and raise wages to workers.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] To this end, he needed to buy out Carnegie and several other major producers and integrate them into one company, thereby eliminating duplication and waste.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He concluded negotiations on March 2, 1901, and formed the United States Steel Corporation.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] It was the first corporation in the world with a market capitalization of over $1 billion.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The buyout, secretly negotiated by Charles M.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Schwab), was the largest such industrial takeover in United States history to date.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The holdings were incorporated in the United States Steel Corporation, a trust organized by Morgan, and Carnegie retired from business.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] His steel enterprises were bought out for $303,450,000.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie's share of this amounted to $225.64 million (in 2025, $8.73 billion), which was paid to him in the form of 5%, 50-year gold bonds.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The letter agreeing to sell his share was signed on February 26, 1901.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] On March 2, the circular formally filed the organization and capitalization (at $1.4 billion—4% of the U.S. gross domestic product at the time) of the United States Steel Corporation actually completed the contract.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The bonds were to be delivered within two weeks to the Hudson Trust Company of Hoboken, New Jersey, in trust to Robert A.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] There, a special vault was built to house the physical bulk of nearly $230 million worth of bonds.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie continued his business career; some of his literary intentions were fulfilled.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He befriended the English poet Matthew Arnold, the English philosopher Herbert Spencer, and the American humorist Mark Twain, as well as being in correspondence and acquaintance with most of the U.S.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Presidents, statesmen, and notable writers.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie constructed commodious swimming-baths for the people of his hometown in Dunfermline in 1879.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In the following year, Carnegie gave £8,000 for the establishment of a Dunfermline Carnegie Library in Scotland.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1884, he gave $50,000 to Bellevue Hospital Medical College (now part of New York University Medical Center) to create a histological laboratory, now called the Carnegie Laboratory.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1881, Carnegie took his family, including his 70-year-old mother, on a trip to the United Kingdom.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] They toured Scotland by coach and enjoyed several receptions en route.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The highlight was a return to Dunfermline, where Carnegie's mother laid the foundation stone of a Carnegie Library which he funded.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie's criticism of British society did not mean dislike; on the contrary, one of Carnegie's ambitions was to act as a catalyst for a close association between English-speaking peoples.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] To this end, in the early 1880s in partnership with Samuel Storey, he purchased numerous newspapers in Britain, all of which were to advocate the abolition of the monarchy and the establishment of "the British Republic".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie's charm, aided by his wealth, afforded him many British friends, including Prime Minister William Ewart Gladstone.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1886, Carnegie's younger brother Thomas died at age 43.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] While owning steel works, Carnegie had purchased at low cost the most valuable of the iron ore fields around Lake Superior.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Following his tour of the UK, he wrote about his experiences in a book entitled *An American Four-in-hand in Britain*.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1886, Carnegie wrote his most radical work to date, entitled *Triumphant Democracy*.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Liberal in its use of statistics to make its arguments, the book argued his view that the American republican system of government was superior to the British monarchical system.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] It gave a highly favorable and idealized view of American progress and criticized the British royal family.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The cover depicted an upended royal crown and a broken scepter.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The book created considerable controversy in the UK.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The book made many Americans appreciate their country's economic progress and sold over 40,000 copies, mostly in the U.S.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Although actively involved in running his many businesses, Carnegie had become a regular contributor to numerous magazines, most notably *The Nineteenth Century*, under the editorship of James Knowles, and the influential *North American Review*, led by the editor Lloyd Bryce.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1889, Carnegie published "Wealth" in the June issue of the *North American Review*.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] After reading it, Gladstone requested its publication in Britain, where it appeared as "The Gospel of Wealth" in *The Pall Mall Gazette*.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie argued that the life of a wealthy industrialist should comprise two parts.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The first part was the gathering and the accumulation of wealth.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The second part was for the subsequent distribution of this wealth to benevolent causes.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Philanthropy was key to making life worthwhile.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In the aftermath of the Spanish–American War, the United States seemed poised to annex Cuba, Guam, Puerto Rico and the Philippines.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie strongly opposed the idea of American colonies.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He opposed the annexation of the Philippines almost to the point of supporting William Jennings Bryan against McKinley in 1900.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1898, Carnegie tried to arrange independence for the Philippines.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] As the conclusion of the Spanish–American War neared, the United States purchased the Philippines from Spain for $20 million.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] To counter what he perceived as American imperialism, Carnegie personally offered $20 million to the Philippines so that the Filipino people could purchase their independence from the United States.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1898 Carnegie joined the American Anti-Imperialist League, in opposition to the U.S. annexation of the Philippines.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Its membership included former presidents of the United States Grover Cleveland and Benjamin Harrison and literary figures such as Mark Twain.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie spent his last years as a philanthropist.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] From 1901 forward, public attention was turned from the shrewd business acumen which had enabled Carnegie to accumulate such a fortune, to the public-spirited way in which he devoted himself to using it on philanthropic projects.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He had written about his views on social subjects and the responsibilities of great wealth in *Triumphant Democracy* (1886) and *Gospel of Wealth* (1889).
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie devoted the rest of his life to providing capital for purposes of public interest and social and educational advancement.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He provided $25,000 a year to the movement for spelling reform.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] His organization, the Simplified Spelling Board, created the *Handbook of Simplified Spelling*, which was written wholly in reformed spelling.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Among his many philanthropic efforts, the establishment of public libraries throughout the United States, Britain, Canada, New Zealand, and mostly other English-speaking countries was especially prominent.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In this special driving interest of his, Carnegie was inspired by meetings with philanthropist Enoch Pratt (1808–1896).
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie turned over management of the library project by 1908 to his staff, led by James Bertram (1874–1934).
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The first Carnegie Library opened in 1883 in Dunfermline.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] His method was to provide funds to build and equip the library, but only on the condition that the local authority matched that by providing the land and a budget for operation and maintenance.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] To secure local interest, in 1885, he gave $500,000 to Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, for a public library; in 1886, he gave $250,000 to Allegheny City, Pennsylvania, for a music hall and library; and he gave $250,000 to Edinburgh for a free library.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In total, Carnegie funded some 3,000 libraries, located in 47 U.S. states, and also in Canada, Britain, Ireland, Belgium, Serbia, France, Australia, New Zealand, South Africa, the West Indies, and Fiji.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He also donated £50,000 to help set up the University of Birmingham in 1899.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] As Van Slyck (1991) showed, during the last years of the 19th century, there was the increasing adoption of the idea that free libraries should be available to the American public.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] But the design of such libraries was the subject of prolonged and heated debate.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] On one hand, the library profession called for designs that supported efficiency in administration and operation; on the other, wealthy philanthropists favored buildings that reinforced the paternalistic metaphor and enhanced civic pride.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Between 1886 and 1917, Carnegie reformed both library philanthropy and library design, encouraging a closer correspondence between the two.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie's libraries also served as institutions of control.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] According to the historian Richard White, many steelworkers employed by Carnegie "despised" his library in Homestead, Pennsylvania.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1900, Carnegie gave $2 million to start the Carnegie Institute of Technology (CIT) at Pittsburgh and the same amount in 1902 to create the Carnegie Institution at Washington, D.C., to encourage research and discovery.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He later contributed more to these and other schools.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] CIT is now known as Carnegie Mellon University after it merged with the Mellon Institute of Industrial Research.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie also served on the Boards of Cornell University and Stevens Institute of Technology.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] I should like to be satisfied before I depart, that we are going to repay to the old land some part of the debt we owe them by revealing more clearly than ever to them the new heavens." The telescope saw first light on November 2, 1917, with Carnegie still alive.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1901, in Scotland, he gave $10 million to establish the Carnegie Trust for the Universities of Scotland.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] It was created by a deed that he signed on June 7, 1901, and it was incorporated by royal charter on August 21, 1902.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The establishing gift of $10 million was then an unprecedented sum: at the time, total government assistance to all four Scottish universities was about £50,000 a year.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The aim of the Trust was to improve and extend the opportunities for scientific research in the Scottish universities and to enable the deserving and qualified youth of Scotland to attend a university.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He was subsequently elected Lord Rector of University of St.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Andrews in December 1901, and formally installed as such in October 1902, serving until 1907.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He also donated large sums of money to Dunfermline, the place of his birth.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In addition to a library, Carnegie also bought the private estate which became Pittencrieff Park and opened it to all members of the public, establishing the Carnegie Dunfermline Trust to benefit the people of Dunfermline.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] A statue of Carnegie was later built between 1913 and 1914 in the park as a commemoration for his creation of the park.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He was a founding financial backer of Jeannette Thurber's National Conservatory of Music of America in 1885.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He built the music performing venue Carnegie Hall in New York City; it opened in 1891 and remained in his family until 1925.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] His interest in music led him to fund the construction of 7,000 pipe organs in churches and temples, with no apparent preference for any religious denomination or sect.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He gave a further $10 million in 1913 to endow the Carnegie United Kingdom Trust, a grant-making foundation.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He transferred to the trust the charge of all his existing and future benefactions, other than university benefactions in the United Kingdom.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He gave the trustees a wide discretion, and they inaugurated a policy of financing rural library schemes rather than erecting library buildings, and of assisting the musical education of the people rather than granting organs to churches.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1901, Carnegie also established large pension funds for his former employees at Homestead and, in 1905, for American college professors.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] One critical requirement was that church-related schools had to sever their religious connections to get his money.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie was a large benefactor of the Tuskegee Institute for Black American education under Booker T.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He helped Washington create the National Negro Business League.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1904, he founded the Carnegie Hero Fund for the United States and Canada (a few years later also established in the United Kingdom, Switzerland, Norway, Sweden, France, Italy, the Netherlands, Belgium, Denmark, and Germany) for the recognition of deeds of heroism.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie contributed $1.5 million in 1903 for the erection of the Peace Palace at The Hague; and he donated $150,000 for a Pan-American Palace in Washington as a home for the International Bureau of American Republics.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] When it became obvious that Carnegie could not give away his entire fortune within his lifetime, he established the Carnegie Corporation of New York in 1911 "to promote the advancement and diffusion of knowledge and understanding" and continue his program of giving.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie was honored for his philanthropy and support of the arts by initiation as an honorary member of Phi Mu Alpha Sinfonia fraternity on October 14, 1917, at the New England Conservatory of Music in Boston, Massachusetts.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The fraternity's mission reflects Carnegie's values by developing young men to share their talents to create harmony in the world.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie died on August 11, 1919, in Lenox, Massachusetts, at his Shadow Brook estate, of bronchial pneumonia.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He had already given away $350,695,653 (approximately $6.9 billion in 2025 dollars) of his wealth.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] After his death, his last $30 million was given to foundations, charities, and to pensioners.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He was buried at Sleepy Hollow Cemetery in Sleepy Hollow, New York.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] His intentionally simple gravestone, in the form of the Celtic cross, is located on the Arcadia Hebron plot of land at the corner of Summit Avenue and Dingle Road.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie is buried only a few yards away from union organizer Samuel Gompers, another important figure of industry in the Gilded Age.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie was one of more than 50 members of the South Fork Fishing and Hunting Club, which has been blamed for the Johnstown Flood that killed 2,209 people in 1889.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] At the suggestion of his friend Benjamin Ruff, Carnegie's partner Henry Clay Frick had formed the exclusive South Fork Fishing and Hunting Club high above Johnstown, Pennsylvania.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The sixty-odd club members were the leading business tycoons of Western Pennsylvania and included among their number Frick's best friend, Andrew Mellon, his attorneys Philander Knox and James Hay Reed, as well as Frick's business partner, Carnegie.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] High above the city, near the small town of South Fork, the South Fork Dam was originally built between 1838 and 1853 by the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania as part of a canal system to be used as a reservoir for a canal basin in Johnstown.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] With the coming-of-age of railroads superseding canal barge transport, the lake was abandoned by the Commonwealth, sold to the Pennsylvania Railroad, and sold again to private interests, and eventually came to be owned by the South Fork Fishing and Hunting Club in 1881.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Prior to the flood, speculators had purchased the abandoned reservoir, made less than well-engineered repairs to the old dam, raised the lake level, built cottages and a clubhouse, and created the South Fork Fishing and Hunting Club.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Less than 20 miles (32 km) downstream from the dam sat the city of Johnstown.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The dam was 72 feet (22 m) high and 931 feet (284 m) long.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Between 1881, when the club was opened, and 1889, the dam frequently sprang leaks and was patched, mostly with mud and straw.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Additionally, a previous owner removed and sold for scrap the three cast iron discharge pipes that previously allowed a controlled release of water.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] There had been some speculation as to the dam's integrity, and concerns had been raised by the head of the Cambria Iron Works downstream in Johnstown.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Such repair work, a reduction in height, and unusually high snowmelt and heavy spring rains combined to cause the dam to give way on May 31, 1889, resulting in twenty million tons of water sweeping down the valley as the Johnstown Flood.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] When word of the dam's failure was telegraphed to Pittsburgh, Frick and other members of the South Fork Fishing and Hunting Club gathered to form the Pittsburgh Relief Committee for assistance to the flood victims as well as determining never to speak publicly about the club or the flood.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] This strategy was a success, and Knox and Reed were able to fend off all lawsuits that would have placed blame upon the club's members.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Although Cambria Iron and Steel's facilities were heavily damaged by the flood, they returned to full production within a year.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] After the flood, Carnegie built Johnstown a new library to replace the one built by Cambria's chief legal counsel Cyrus Elder, which was destroyed in the flood.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The Carnegie-donated library is now owned by the Johnstown Area Heritage Association and houses the Flood Museum.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The Homestead Strike was a bloody labor confrontation lasting 143 days in 1892, one of the most serious in U.S. history.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The conflict was centered on Carnegie Steel's main plant in Homestead, Pennsylvania, and grew out of a labor dispute between the Amalgamated Association of Iron and Steel Workers (AA) and the Carnegie Steel Company.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie left on a trip to Scotland before the unrest peaked.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In doing so, Carnegie left mediation of the dispute in the hands of his associate and partner Henry Clay Frick.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Frick was well known in industrial circles for maintaining staunch anti-union sentiment.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] With the collective bargaining agreement between the union and company expiring at the end of June, Frick and the leaders of the local AA union entered into negotiations in February.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] With the steel industry doing well and prices higher, the AA asked for a wage increase; the AA represented about 800 of the 3,800 workers at the plant.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Frick immediately countered with an average 22% wage decrease that would affect nearly half the union's membership and remove a number of positions from the bargaining unit.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The union and company failed to come to an agreement, and management locked the union out.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Workers considered the stoppage a "lockout" by management and not a "strike" by workers.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] As such, the workers would have been well within their rights to protest, and subsequent government action would have been a set of criminal procedures designed to crush what was seen as a pivotal demonstration of the growing labor rights movement, strongly opposed by management.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Frick brought in thousands of strikebreakers to work the steel mills and Pinkerton agents to safeguard them.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] On July 6, the arrival of a force of 300 Pinkerton agents from New York City and Chicago resulted in a fight in which 10 men — seven strikers and three Pinkertons — were killed and hundreds were injured.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Pennsylvania Governor Robert Pattison ordered two brigades of the state militia to the strike site.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Then allegedly in response to the fight between the striking workers and the Pinkertons, anarchist Alexander Berkman shot at Frick in an attempted assassination, wounding him.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] While not directly connected to the strike, Berkman was tied in for the assassination attempt.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] According to Berkman, "... with the elimination of Frick, responsibility for Homestead conditions would rest with Carnegie." Afterwards, the company successfully resumed operations with non-union immigrant employees in place of the Homestead plant workers, and Carnegie returned to the United States.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] However, Carnegie's reputation was permanently damaged by the Homestead events.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] According to David Nasaw, after 1898, when the United States entered a war with Spain, Carnegie increasingly devoted his energy to supporting pacifism.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He strongly opposed the war and the subsequent imperialistic American takeover of the Philippines.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] When Theodore Roosevelt became president in 1901, Carnegie and Roosevelt were in frequent contact.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] They exchanged letters, communicated through mutual friends such as Secretary of State John Hay, and met in person.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie hoped that Roosevelt would turn the Philippines free.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He saluted Roosevelt for forcing Germany and Britain to arbitrate their conflict with Venezuela in 1903, and especially for becoming the mediator who negotiated an end to the war between Russia and Japan in 1907–1908.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Roosevelt relied on Carnegie for financing his expedition to Africa in 1909.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In return he asked the ex-president to mediate the growing conflict between the cousins who ruled Britain and Germany.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Roosevelt started to do so but the scheme collapsed when king Edward VII suddenly died.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Nasaw argues that Roosevelt systematically deceived and manipulated Carnegie and held the elderly man in contempt.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie did not want to marry during his mother's lifetime, instead choosing to take care of her in her illness towards the end of her life.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] After she died in 1886, the 51-year-old Carnegie married Louise Whitfield, who was 21 years his junior.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] In 1897, the couple had their only child, Margaret, whom they named after Carnegie's mother.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie bought Skibo Castle in Scotland in 1898 for some $85,000.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] He and his small family spent most summers there, traveling between Scotland and his adopted United States by ocean liner.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The Carnegies made their home partly at Skibo and partly in their New York mansion located at 2 East 91st Street at Fifth Avenue.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] Carnegie lived there until his death in 1919, and his wife Louise continued to live there until her death in 1946.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The building has been used since 1976 as the Cooper-Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum, part of the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The surrounding neighborhood on Manhattan's Upper East Side has come to be called Carnegie Hill.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p01] The mansion was designated as a National Historic Landmark in 1966.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie gave "formal allegiance" to the Republican Party, though he was said to be "a violent opponent of some of the most sacred doctrines" of the party.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] In his final days, Carnegie had pneumonia.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Before his death on August 11, 1919, Carnegie had donated $350,695,654 for various causes.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie was involved in philanthropic causes, but he kept himself away from religious circles.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] He wanted to be identified by the world as a "positivist".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] He was highly influenced in public life by John Bright.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] As early as 1868, at age 33, he drafted a memo to himself.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] The amassing of wealth is one of the worse species of idolatry.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie wrote "The Gospel of Wealth", an article in which he stated his belief that the rich should use their wealth to help enrich society.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie claimed to be a champion of evolutionary thought—particularly the work of Herbert Spencer, even declaring Spencer his teacher.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] However although Carnegie claimed to be a disciple of Spencer, many of his actions went against the ideas he espoused.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Spencerian evolution was for individual rights and against government interference.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Furthermore, Spencerian evolution held that those unfit to sustain themselves must be allowed to perish.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Spencer believed that just as there were many varieties of beetles, respectively modified to existence in a particular place in nature, so too had human society "spontaneously fallen into division of labour".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Spencerian 'survival of the fittest' firmly credits any provisions made to assist the weak, unskilled, poor and distressed to be an imprudent disservice to evolution.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Spencer insisted people should resist for the benefit of collective humanity, as severe fate singles out the weak, debauched, and disabled.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Andrew Carnegie's political and economic focus during the late nineteenth and early twentieth century was the defense of laissez-faire economics.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie emphatically resisted government intrusion in commerce, as well as government-sponsored charities.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie believed the concentration of capital was essential for societal progress and should be encouraged.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie was an ardent supporter of commercial "survival of the fittest" and sought to attain immunity from business challenges by dominating all phases of the steel manufacturing procedure.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie's determination to lower costs included cutting labor expenses as well.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] In a notably Spencerian manner, Carnegie argued that unions impeded the natural reduction of prices by pushing up costs, which blocked evolutionary progress.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie felt that unions represented the narrow interest of the few while his actions benefited the entire community.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] On the surface, Andrew Carnegie appears to be a strict laissez-faire capitalist and follower of Herbert Spencer, often referring to himself as a disciple of Spencer.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Conversely, Carnegie, a titan of industry, seems to embody all of the qualities of Spencerian survival of the fittest.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] The two men enjoyed a mutual respect for one another and maintained a correspondence until Spencer's death in 1903.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] There are, however, some major discrepancies between Spencer's capitalist evolutionary conceptions and Andrew Carnegie's capitalist practices.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Spencer wrote that in production the advantages of the superior individual are comparatively minor, and thus acceptable, yet the benefit that dominance provides those who control a large segment of production might be hazardous to competition.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Spencer feared that an absence of "sympathetic self-restraint" of those with too much power could lead to the ruin of their competitors.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] He did not think free-market competition necessitated competitive warfare.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Furthermore, Spencer argued that individuals with superior resources who deliberately used investment schemes to put competitors out of business were committing acts of "commercial murder".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie built his wealth in the steel industry by maintaining an extensively integrated operating system.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie also bought out some regional competitors, and merged with others, usually maintaining the majority shares in the companies.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Herbert Spencer absolutely was against government interference in business in the form of regulatory limitations, taxes, and tariffs as well.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Spencer saw tariffs as a form of taxation that levied against the majority in service to "the benefit of a small minority of manufacturers and artisans".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Despite Carnegie's personal dedication to Herbert Spencer as a friend, his adherence to Spencer's political and economic ideas is more contentious.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] In particular, it appears Carnegie either misunderstood or intentionally misrepresented some of Spencer's principal arguments.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] On the subject of charity Andrew Carnegie's actions diverged in the most significant and complex manner from Herbert Spencer's philosophies.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] In his 1854 essay "Manners and Fashion", Spencer referred to public education as "Old schemes".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] He went on to declare that public schools and colleges fill the heads of students with inept, useless knowledge and exclude useful knowledge.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Spencer stated that he trusted no organization of any kind, "political, religious, literary, philanthropic", and believed that as they expanded in influence so too did their regulations expand.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] In addition, Spencer thought that as all institutions grow they become ever more corrupted by the influence of power and money.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] The institution eventually loses its "original spirit, and sinks into a lifeless mechanism".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Spencer insisted that all forms of philanthropy that uplift the poor and downtrodden were reckless and incompetent.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Spencer thought any attempt to prevent "the really salutary sufferings" of the less fortunate "bequeath to posterity a continually increasing curse".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie held that societal progress relied on individuals who maintained moral obligations to themselves and to society.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Furthermore, he believed that charity supplied the means for those who wish to improve themselves to achieve their goals.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie urged other wealthy people to contribute to society in the form of parks, works of art, libraries and other endeavors that improve the community and contribute to the "lasting good".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie also held a strong opinion against inherited wealth.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie believed that the sons of prosperous businesspersons were rarely as talented as their fathers.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] By leaving large sums of money to their children, wealthy business leaders were wasting resources that could be used to benefit society.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Most notably, Carnegie believed that the future leaders of society would rise from the ranks of the poor.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie strongly believed in this because he had risen from the bottom.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] He believed the poor possessed an advantage over the wealthy because they receive greater attention from their parents and are taught better work ethics.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie and his family belonged to the Presbyterian Church in the United States of America, also known informally as the Northern Presbyterian Church.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] In his early life Carnegie was skeptical of Calvinism, and religion as a whole, but reconciled with it later in his life.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] In his autobiography, Carnegie describes his family as moderate Presbyterian believers, writing that "there was not one orthodox Presbyterian" in his family; various members of his family having somewhat distanced themselves from Calvinism, some of them leaning more towards Swedenborgianism.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] While a child, his family led vigorous theological and political disputes.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] His mother avoided the topic of religion.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] His father left the Presbyterian church after a sermon on infant damnation, while, according to Carnegie, still remaining very religious on his own.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Witnessing sectarianism and strife in 19th century Scotland regarding religion and philosophy, Carnegie kept his distance from organized religion and theism.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Later in life, Carnegie's firm opposition to religion softened.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] For many years he was a member of Madison Avenue Presbyterian Church, pastored from 1905 to 1926 by Social Gospel exponent Henry Sloane Coffin, while his wife and daughter belonged to the Brick Presbyterian Church.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] He also prepared (but did not deliver) an address in which he professed a belief in "an Infinite and Eternal Energy from which all things proceed".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Records exist of a short period of correspondence around 1912–1913 between Carnegie and 'Abdu'l-Bahá, the eldest son of Bahá'u'lláh, founder of the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] In these letters, one of which was published in *The New York Times* in full text, Carnegie is extolled as a "lover of the world of humanity and one of the founders of Universal Peace".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Influenced by his "favorite living hero in public life", John Bright, Carnegie started his efforts in pursuit of world peace at a young age, and he supported causes that opposed military intervention.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] His motto, "All is well since all grows better", served not only as a good rationalization of his successful business career but also his view of international relations.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Despite his efforts towards international peace, Carnegie faced many dilemmas on his quest.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] These dilemmas are often regarded as conflicts between his view on international relations and his other loyalties.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Throughout the 1880s and 1890s, for example, Carnegie allowed his steel works to fill large orders of armor plate for the building of an enlarged and modernized United States Navy, but he opposed American overseas expansion.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Despite that, Carnegie served as a major donor for the newly established International Court of Arbitration's Peace Palace—brainchild of Russian tsar Nicholas II.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] His largest and, in the long run, most influential peace organization was the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, formed in 1910 with a $10 million endowment.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] In 1914, on the eve of the First World War, Carnegie founded the Church Peace Union (CPU), a group of leaders in religion, academia, and politics.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Through the CPU, Carnegie hoped to mobilize the world's churches, religious organizations, and other spiritual and moral resources to join in promoting moral leadership to put an end to war forever.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] For its inaugural international event, the CPU sponsored a conference to be held on August 1, 1914, on the shores of Lake Constance in southern Germany.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] As the delegates made their way to the conference by train, Germany was invading Belgium.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Despite its inauspicious beginning, the CPU thrived.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Today its focus is on ethics, and it is known as the Carnegie Council for Ethics in International Affairs, an independent, nonpartisan, nonprofit organization, whose mission is to be the voice for ethics in international affairs.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] The outbreak of the First World War was clearly a shock to Carnegie and his optimistic view on world peace.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] On the matter of American colonial expansion, Carnegie had always thought it is an unwise gesture for the United States.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] He did not oppose the annexation of the Hawaiian islands or Puerto Rico, but he opposed the annexation of the Philippines.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie believed that it involved a denial of the fundamental democratic principle, and he also urged William McKinley to withdraw American troops and allow the Filipinos to live with their independence.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] This act strongly impressed the other American anti-imperialists, who soon elected him vice-president of the Anti-Imperialist League.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] After he sold his steel company in 1901, Carnegie was able to get fully involved in the peace cause, both financially and personally.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] He gave away much of his fortunes to various peacekeeping agencies in order to keep them growing.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] When a friend, the British writer William T.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie believed that it is the effort and will of the people, that maintains the peace in international relations.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] If world peace depended solely on financial support, it would not seem a goal, but more like an act of pity.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Like Stead, he believed that the United States and the British Empire would merge into one nation, telling him "We are heading straight to the Re-United States".
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie believed that the combined country's power would maintain world peace and disarmament.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] The creation of the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace in 1910 was regarded as a milestone on the road to the ultimate goal of abolition of war.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Beyond a gift of $10 million for peace promotion, Carnegie also encouraged the "scientific" investigation of the various causes of war, and the adoption of judicial methods that should eventually eliminate them.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] He believed that the Endowment exists to promote information on the nations' rights and responsibilities under existing international law and to encourage other conferences to codify this law.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] In 1899, Andrew Carnegie was awarded American Library Association Honorary Membership.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie received the honorary Doctor of Laws (DLL) from the University of Glasgow in June 1901, and received the Freedom of the City of Glasgow "in recognition of his munificence" later the same year.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Also in 1902, he was elected as a member to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] He received an honorary Doctor of Laws (LLD) from the University of Aberdeen in 1906.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] In 1907, the American Society of Mechanical Engineers elected him an honorary member.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] In 1910, he received the Freedom of the City of Belfast and was made as well Commander of the National Order of the Legion of Honour by the French government.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie was awarded as Knight Grand Cross of the Order of Orange-Nassau by Queen Wilhelmina of the Netherlands on August 25, 1913.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie received July 1, 1914, an honorary doctorate from the University of Groningen the Netherlands.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] His benefactions amounted to $350,000,000—for he gave away not only his annual income of something more than $12,500,000, but most of the principal as well.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Of this sum, $62,000,000 was allotted to the British Empire and $288,000,000 to the United States, for Carnegie, in the main, confined his benefactions to the English-speaking nations.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] These gifts fairly picture Carnegie's conception of the best ways to improve the status of the common man.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] They represent all his personal tastes—his love of books, art, music, and nature—and the reforms which he regarded as most essential to human progress—scientific research, education both literary and technical, and, above all, the abolition of war.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] The expenditure the public most associates with Carnegie's name is that for public libraries.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie himself frequently said that his favorite benefaction was the Hero Fund—among other reasons, because "it came up my ain back"; but probably deep in his own mind his library gifts took precedence over all others in importance.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] There was only one genuine remedy, he believed, for the ills that beset the human race, and that was enlightenment.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] "Let there be light" was the motto that, in the early days, he insisted on placing in all his library buildings.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] As to the greatest endowment of all, the Carnegie Corporation, that was merely Andrew Carnegie in permanently organized form; it was established to carry on, after Carnegie's death, the work to which he had given personal attention in his own lifetime.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie's personal papers are at the Library of Congress Manuscript Division.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] These collections deal primarily with Carnegie philanthropy and have very little personal material related to Carnegie.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie Mellon University and the Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh jointly administer the Andrew Carnegie Collection of digitized archives on Carnegie's life.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] By the standards of 19th-century tycoons, Carnegie was not a particularly ruthless man but a humanitarian with enough acquisitiveness to go in the ruthless pursuit of money.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] To some, Carnegie represents the idea of the American dream.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] He was an immigrant from Scotland who came to America and became successful.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] He is not only known for his successes but his huge amounts of philanthropic works, not only for charities but also to promote democracy and independence to colonized countries.
[src:alexander-crombie-humphreys/andrew-carnegie-p02] Carnegie was a frequent contributor to periodicals on labor issues.
